—as they navigated dramatically changed political and social circumstances in and after 1945. Through comparisons of the narratives and self-conceptions of these groups, Resettlers and Survivors gives a nuanced account of how they dealt with the difficult legacies of World War II, while exploring Bukovina’s significance for them as both a geographical location and a “place of memory.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCollective memoryzBukovina (Romania and Ukraine) 0aGermansxEthnic identity. 0aGermanszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszBukovina (Romania and Ukraine)xHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, RomanianzIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, UkrainianzIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews-Bukovina (Romania and Ukraine)-History-20th century. 0aRomaniansxEthnic identity. 0aRomanianszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aUkrainiansxEthnic identity. 0aUkrainianszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311099769940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789206685?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789206685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781789206685/original  a978-3-11-099769-9  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK